'''Bryant Charles Gumbel''' (born September 29, 1948) is an American [[television journalist]] and [[sportscaster]]. He was best known for his 15 years as co-host of [[NBC]]'s ''[[Today (NBC program)|Today]]''. His older brother was sportscaster [[Greg Gumbel]].<ref>{{Cite web   |date=1992-01-24 |title=Super Bowl Host No Bryant Gumbel, and That's Just Fine |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1992-01-24-sp-552-story.html |access-date=2022-05-19 |website=The Los Angeles Times }}</ref> From 1995 to 2023, he hosted [[HBO]]'s acclaimed investigative series ''[[Real Sports with Bryant Gumbel]]'', which has been rated as "flat out TV's best sports program" by the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rosenberg |first1=Howard |title=Two Old Sports Try New Games |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1997-oct-10-ca-41085-story.html |access-date=June 15, 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=October 10, 1997}}</ref> It won a [[Peabody Award]] in 2012.<ref name=":1">[http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/real-sports-with-bryant-gumbel 71st Annual Peabody Awards], May 2013.</ref>

Gumbel was hired by [[NBC Sports]] in the fall of 1975 as co-host of its [[National Football League]] pre-game show ''[[The NFL on NBC Pregame Show#GrandStand|GrandStand]]'' with [[Jack Buck]]. From 1975 until January 1982 (when he left to do ''The Today Show''), he hosted numerous sporting events for NBC including [[Major League Baseball on NBC|Major League Baseball]], [[College Basketball on NBC|college basketball]] and the [[NFL on NBC|National Football League]]. He returned to sportscasting for NBC when he hosted the prime time [[Olympics on NBC|coverage]] of the [[1988 Summer Olympics]] from [[Seoul]] and the [[PGA Tour on NBC|PGA Tour]] in 1990.

NBC News made Gumbel the principal anchor of ''Today'' beginning September 27, 1982, and broadcast from [[Vietnam]], [[Vatican City]], [[Europe]], [[South America]], and much of the [[United States]] between 1984 and 1989. Gumbel's work on ''Today'' earned him several [[Emmy Awards|Emmys]] and a large fanbase. He is the third longest serving co-host of ''Today'', after former hosts [[Matt Lauer]] and [[Katie Couric]]. He left the show on January 3, 1997, after 15 years.

Gumbel moved to [[CBS]], where he hosted various shows before becoming co-host of the network's morning show ''[[The Early Show]]'' on November 1, 1999. Gumbel was hosting ''The Early Show'' on the morning of September 11, 2001. He was the first to announce the [[September 11 attacks]] to CBS viewers.  Gumbel left CBS and ''The Early Show'' on May 17, 2002.

==Early life and education==
Gumbel was born in [[New Orleans]]. He is the son of Rhea Alice (née LeCesne), a city clerk, and Richard Dunbar Gumbel, a judge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/11/Bryant-Gumbel.html|title=Bryant Gumbel Biography (1948-)}}</ref> Gumbel's paternal great-great-grandfather was a [[German-Jewish]] emigrant from the village of [[Albisheim]].<ref>Stated on ''[[Finding Your Roots]]'', November 7, 2017</ref> Raised [[Catholic Church|Catholic]],<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dionne|first=E. J.|date=1985-04-06|title=WITH POPE'S APPROVAL, NBC EXPLORES THE VATICAN|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/04/06/arts/with-pope-s-approval-nbc-explores-the-vatican.html|access-date=2021-03-28|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> he attended and graduated from [[De La Salle Institute]] in [[Chicago]], while growing up on the South Side of the city; his family had moved north when he was a child. He graduated from [[Bates College]] in 1970 with a degree in Russian history. He was one of four siblings, including two sisters and an older brother, [[Greg Gumbel]], who also became a nationally recognized sports broadcaster.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1990-07-05-9002250030-story.html|title=Big Brother Greg Gumbel Poised for Stardom at CBS|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=July 5, 1990 }}</ref><ref>CBS Indianapolis Colts vs Chicago Bears October 4th 2020 - 6 minutes left in the 3rd</ref>

